AB  - IRS-P4, a 3-axis body stabilized earth-pointing satellite meant for oceanographic applications was launched on 26th May 1999. During its 7 years of on orbit life, the satellite had to encounter a series of power problems, which reduced the onboard power generation. The power crisis jeopardized not only the continuation of payload services but also the very survival of the mission. A strategy was then devised to over come this crippling power crisis and to extend the useful mission life for providing payload data to global user community. The strategy was to hold the inertial attitude of the satellite during all non-imaging orbits such that the solar panels were oriented towards sun thereby ensuring good power generation. Whenever payload operations were to be carried out, the spacecraft was brought back to earth pointing mode. Thus, the spacecraft had two attitude orientations, one to satisfy payload requirements and the other one to satisfy power requirements. However, this strategy had some associated issues, like thermal management and attitude stabilization (because of gyro drifts due to temperature variations caused by the different orientations). Novel methods and judicious planning of spacecraft operations on a daily basis addressed both these issues. This strategy was put into effect from 26 January 2006 onwards, after which sufficient power generation during nonpayload orbits was ensured. This allowed enough power generation to cater up to 6 payload operations a day. This approach has led to extending the useful life of India's only oceanographic spacecraft. This paper addresses the challenges that were involved and the methods by which they were overcome. Copyright IAF/IAA. All rights reserved.
