AB  - The São Pedro de Caldas (SPC) massif is the southeasternmost occurrence of a nearly continuous belt of foliated mangerite-granite tabular bodies which runs NW-SE for about 100 km within the Guaxupé Domain, an allochtonous terrane in the southern border of the São Francisco craton, Brazil, made up of rocks affected by a strong Neoproterozoic (650-620 Ma) metamorphic overprint. Greenish, medium- to coarse-grained mangerites are predominant in the SPC massif; pink hornblende granites are more abundant in its central portion, while fine-grained charnockites occur as scattered metric bodies within the mangerites. The strong metamorphic overprint (peaking at T = 750-800°C and P ≥ 7 kbar, as estimated from the pyroxene compositions) destroyed the magmatic textures and provoked exsolution and chemical reequilibration of the pyroxenes, feldspars and Fe-Ti oxides. A "within-plate" chemical signature is indicated by low mg#, Ca and Sr and high Zr. Slight but systematic variations in the mg# are observed among the three sectors in which the massif is divided; they are lower in the Eastern (7-9 in mangerites) as compared to the Central sector (from 17 in the mangerites down to 12 in fractionated granites), suggesting that slightly different parent melts gave rise to the different sectors of the massif. These differences are also shown by the mafic minerals, which approach pure iron-rich end-members in the Eastern sector (opx: Fs85-87; amphibole: hastingsitic hornblende with mg# = 8-11; biotite near pure annite). Contrasts in the contents of Al, Na, K, Ba and Sr observed among mangerites from different sectors of the massif are mostly due to variations in the contents of cumulative Na-K feldspar, which are greater in the Western sector, where the positive Eu anomalies seen in the REE patterns are more pronounced. Chemical modeling shows that in situ crystal fractionation involving oligoclase + K-feldspar (or a single ternary feldspar), ortho- and clinopyroxene and a Fe-Ti oxide is compatible with the observed major element variations in the mangerite-hornblende granite range. The major element variation towards more fractionated rocks (hololeucocratic granites at 75 wt% SiO2) is satisfactorily reproduced by feldspar + hornblende + Fe-Ti oxide extraction, but some mistif is observed with trace element modeling, where some elements (e.g. LREE, Th) attain values higher than expected, implying F (fraction of melt remaining) values lower than predicted by major element modeling (more primitive parent magmas?) or open-system behavior. As inferred from mineralogy and geochemistry, the parent magmas of the SPC mangerite-granite suite were derived from lower-crustal depleted granulites at very low a(H2O) and high T (ca. 950°C). The volumetrically minor fine-grained charnockites (with lower Rb and Th contents and well-displayed positive Eu anomalies but no other indications of cumulative character) would require an even more depleted source. The granites present in the massif share many chemical features with classic rapakivi granites, differing only in their lower Rb, Th and Nb contents, a clear reflection of their lower-crustal source. The generation of the mangerite-granite magmatism (U-Pb ages at ca. 630 Ma) occurred soon after extensive generation of high-K calc-alkaline granitoids (ca. 650 Ma), and seems intimately related to a huge thermal anomaly which ascended rapidly in the crust, provoking high-grade metamorphism and wide-spread migmatization in more fertile protoliths found in the intermediate crustal levels where the mangeritic magmas intruded.
